Seconded on both counts. A compulsion that's actively affecting all humans worldwide is a neat twist, and it being one that actually needs to be preserved in small, controlled population as it's still vital for the species' continued survival (much as it was probably key to our rise up the food chain) adds a layer of Shamayalanness.

But I didn't get the  bit until it was pointed out, because in the kayfabe version it was still just some rogue agents within the SCP itself (does that count as a GoI/PoI when it's internal bad actors?), and under the reveal it's just a deliberate act by the Foundation administration proper with the truth simply being classified at a higher level than most of the staff has access to. Are the overseers and other high level directorship (including the EC) considered GoIs now, because of the great number of things they know and do that the rest of the organisation lack the clearance to be privy to?

There's probably other cliches that could be applied even so if only having one is considered not enough, though.





